We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the accounting personnel to demand immediate settlement or liquidation of cash advances and/or cause the withholding of the amount due from the concerned officials and employees to compel them to settle their accounts. Management may resort to legal action if no settlement is made after sending three (3) demand letters;
Cease from granting of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given is first settled or proper accounting thereof is made;
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to update monthly the subsidiary ledgers and submit to the audit team on a quarterly basis for monitoring; and
No cash advance shall be granted to Acting Municipal Treasurer unless a year-end balance of ₱ 7,120,461.83 is liquidated.

3.10	We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:

3.10.1	Require the GSO - Designate and Municipal Accountant - for current purchases onwards-to religiously prepare and maintain the Property Cards and Ledger Cards, and reconcile both records regularly pending completion of one-time cleansing;

3.10.2	Instruct the GSO - Designate to issue PAR to end users for all issuances of property and equipment; 

3.10.3	Given the enormity of workload involving one time-cleansing of PPE, consider implementing the PPE cleansing by phase (i.e. by PPE class). Thereafter, require Inventory Committee and the Accountant to submit to the audit Team the reports and documents required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 as appropriate, for verification;

3.10.4	Instruct the Inventory Committee to annually conduct and prepare physical count of properties including Road Networks in order to monitor existence of the said properties, not to mention their physical condition;

3.10.5	Recognized the subject landholdings as assets under the PPE-Land account, using the market values indicated in the Tax Declarations as the basis for initial recognition, in accordance with IPSAS 17; and

3.10.6	Obtain official land titles in the name of the Municipality for the land occupied by the Municipal Hall and Public Market of Baliangao.

We recommended that management:

Demand immediate settlement or liquidation of cash advances and/or cause the withholding of the amount due from the concerned officials and employees to compel them to settle their accounts. Management may resort to legal action if no settlement is made after sending three (3) demand letters;
Cease from granting of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given is first settled or proper accounting thereof is made;
Stop the practice of granting cash advances to elective officials for purposes other than that of travelling expenses; and
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to update monthly the subsidiary ledgers and dig up records to substantiate the prior years’ balance with no details.

We recommended that management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary correcting entries to recognize completed projects as of December 31, 2023 and subsequently recognize corresponding depreciation expense. Moreover, adjust in the books the capitalized Reagents for Semi-Automatic Chemistry Analyzer which are consumable;
Designate a full-time General Services Officer (GSO) who will be responsible for the preservation, maintenance, and safekeeping of the PPEs of the LGU;
Create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members with at least one member each from the Accounting Unit and Supply Unit;
Pending the cleansing of the PPE account, require the municipal accountant and the GSO to maintain separate ledger and property cards and PAR for acquisitions of PPE in C.Y. 2024 onwards and to conduct regular reconciliation of records; and
Direct the Inventory Committee to fast-track the completion of the one-time cleansing of PPE following the procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006, to address unreconciled balances of PPE and to fairly present the PPE balances in the financial statements.

We therefore recommended that management undertake the following measures:

Fill-up or designate a full-time Municipal Planning and Development Officer;
Direct the Municipal Development Council (MDC) to update the Annual Investment Plan through a revisit of the unimplemented development projects and review its viability and necessity, and strictly observe the guidelines set in DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1 dated November 4, 2020, as well as other budgeting guidelines;
Enjoin the Municipal Development Council (MDC) to identify and include only in the Annual Investment Plan those programs, projects and activities that are implementable within the calendar year; and
Require the Acting MPDO to regularly monitor and evaluate the implementation of the projects and programs and to apprise the Municipal Budget Office for possible realignments. Ensure that excess appropriations from completed projects are realigned periodically.

We have recommended that the  management incorporate in its APP the mode of procurement for Mangrove  Greening Program should the project be continued in the forthcoming years;

Require the contractor to submit a report on employments generated and payments thereof;

Have the contractor submit its accomplishment report based on the plans and specifications, and such accomplishment should be verified and bear approval from concerned municipal officials;

Direct the concerned municipal officials for the strict monitoring of the program as basis in evaluating the attainment of objectives and guide in formulating prospective actions relating the program.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and Treasury Unit (in the absence of a separate Supply Unit) and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
Provide appropriate manpower for the efficient and effective execution of the supply and property management of the LGU;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/ personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries

We recommended that:
The designated special implementing unit spearheaded by the Municipal Agriculturist properly monitor and implement the project and comply with the provisions of the MOA and the project proposal duly approved by the DA;
The Municipality communicate in writing any progress, changes, delay or any concern relating to the complete and effective implementation of the project to the Undersecretary of Livestock and the DA Regional Field Office, in accordance with the MOA;
The Municipal Agriculturist submit the lacking documents for its request for relief of accountability; and
The Municipal Accountant record in its books the cattle in custody as assets of the Municipality.

We recommended that the management:
Submit to this office the lacking documents for evaluation;
Strictly comply with the prescribed documentary requirements as set out in the revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and in other issuances by regulating bodies including the GPPB and COA;
Ensure the submission and/or keeping of documents with regard the suppliers including, but not limited to, business permits, PCAB licenses, among others, to guarantee the legal, technical, and financial capabilities of suppliers;
Make sure that documents are properly and completely filled out and labeled; and
Abide by the posting requirements indicated in the existing rules and regulations in order to foster transparency.

